---

<PageShell
  title="Netherlands Freelancer Visa 2026: DAFT, Requirements & Insurance Guide"
  description="Complete guide to the Dutch Self-Employment Residence Permit (Zelfstandig ondernemer). DAFT treaty for US citizens, points system, mandatory Dutch health insurance, and step-by-step application process."
  headline="Netherlands Freelancer Visa: Insurance & Requirements Guide"
  subheadline="Everything you need to know about freelancing in the Netherlands—DAFT treaty advantages, the points-based system, mandatory Dutch health insurance, and the complete application process."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Expat Insurance"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/netherlands-hero-bg.png"
>

  <!-- Trust Signals -->
  <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 mb-8 text-sm text-neutral-600">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Updated February 2026
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      Official IND Requirements
    </span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1">
      <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-green-600" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 20 20"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M10 18a8 8 0 100-16 8 8 0 000 16zm3.707-9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414-1.414L9 10.586 7.707 9.293a1 1 0 00-1.414 1.414l2 2a1 1 0 001.414 0l4-4z" clip-rule="evenodd"></path></svg>
      DAFT Treaty Eligible
    </span>
  </div>

  <!-- Section: Overview -->
  <section id="overview" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands has become one of Europe's top destinations for freelancers and entrepreneurs, thanks to its business-friendly environment, high English proficiency, and central EU location. The Self-Employment Residence Permit (Zelfstandig ondernemer) allows non-EU nationals to live and work as freelancers in the Netherlands.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      What makes the Netherlands particularly attractive is the DAFT treaty—the Dutch-American Friendship Treaty—which offers US and Japanese citizens a significantly easier path to self-employment. Instead of navigating the complex points system, DAFT applicants need only show €4,500 in business capital and a viable business plan.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts: Netherlands Freelancer Visa</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-primary-800">
        <li>• <strong>Official name:</strong> Self-Employment Residence Permit (Zelfstandig ondernemer)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Healthcare:</strong> Mandatory Dutch basic insurance (basisverzekering) ~€120-150/month</li>
        <li>• <strong>DAFT advantage:</strong> US/Japan citizens need only €4,500 investment</li>
        <li>• <strong>Standard path:</strong> Points-based system (100 points required)</li>
        <li>• <strong>Duration:</strong> 2 years initial, renewable</li>
        <li>• <strong>Path to PR:</strong> 5 years to permanent residence</li>
        <li>• <strong>30% ruling:</strong> Tax benefit for qualifying expats</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Why Freelance in the Netherlands?</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>DAFT treaty:</strong> US and Japanese citizens get a streamlined path with lower requirements</li>
      <li><strong>English fluency:</strong> Over 90% of Dutch people speak English—daily business is easy</li>
      <li><strong>EU market access:</strong> Gateway to 450 million consumers across the EU</li>
      <li><strong>Strong startup ecosystem:</strong> Amsterdam ranks among Europe's top tech hubs</li>
      <li><strong>30% ruling:</strong> Qualifying expats can receive 30% of salary tax-free for up to 5 years</li>
      <li><strong>Excellent infrastructure:</strong> World-class internet, transport, and logistics</li>
      <li><strong>Quality of life:</strong> High living standards, work-life balance, cycling culture</li>
      <li><strong>Central location:</strong> Easy travel to UK, Germany, Belgium, France</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Key Cities for Freelancers</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Amsterdam</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Tech hub, creative industries, highest costs but most opportunities. Strong international community.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Rotterdam</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Architecture, logistics, port industries. More affordable than Amsterdam, growing startup scene.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">The Hague</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">International organizations, legal sector, government. Many expats, beach access.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Utrecht</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">University city, central location, more affordable. Growing tech and creative sectors.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Quick Decision Guide -->
  <section id="quick-decision" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Quick Decision Guide</h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Netherlands is Right For You If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ You're a US or Japanese citizen (DAFT advantage)</li>
          <li>✓ You work in tech, creative, or consulting fields</li>
          <li>✓ You want EU market access from a central hub</li>
          <li>✓ You prefer English as your working language</li>
          <li>✓ You value work-life balance and cycling</li>
          <li>✓ You can handle high living costs (especially housing)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Consider Other Options If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• You're not from the US/Japan and lack business experience (points system is tough)</li>
          <li>• You want lower living costs (try Portugal, Spain)</li>
          <li>• You prefer warmer weather year-round</li>
          <li>• You want faster path to citizenship (Netherlands requires 5 years)</li>
          <li>• You can't meet mandatory Dutch health insurance costs</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>DAFT treaty advantage:</strong> If you're a US or Japanese citizen, the Netherlands offers one of the easiest freelancer visa paths in Europe. The €4,500 investment requirement is much lower than Germany's requirements, and you don't need to prove your business adds "value" to the Dutch economy through a points system.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Visa Requirements -->
  <section id="requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Requirements</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands has two main paths for self-employed residence: the DAFT treaty route (for US and Japanese citizens) and the standard points-based system (for everyone else). The DAFT route is significantly simpler and has lower requirements.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={requirementsColumns} rows={requirementsRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">DAFT Treaty (US and Japanese Citizens)</h3>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">DAFT Requirements</h4>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>• <strong>Investment:</strong> €4,500 minimum in Dutch bank account or business</li>
        <li>• <strong>Business plan:</strong> Clear outline of your business activities</li>
        <li>• <strong>Valid passport:</strong> US or Japanese passport</li>
        <li>• <strong>Clean record:</strong> No criminal record certificate may be required</li>
        <li>• <strong>Health insurance:</strong> Proof of adequate coverage</li>
        <li>• <strong>Housing:</strong> Proof of Dutch address (can arrange after arrival)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The DAFT treaty dates back to 1956 and was designed to promote trade between the US and Netherlands. Japan was added later under a similar treaty. Unlike the standard path, DAFT applicants don't need to prove their business creates jobs or adds innovation—they just need to show they have a viable business.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Standard Points System (Non-DAFT)</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      If you're not eligible for DAFT, you'll need to score at least 100 points across three categories. This system is designed to attract entrepreneurs who bring significant value to the Dutch economy.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={pointsColumns} rows={pointsRows} />

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mt-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Points Are Scored</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Education:</strong> Higher degrees earn more points</li>
          <li>• <strong>Age:</strong> 25-44 years old scores highest</li>
          <li>• <strong>Experience:</strong> Prior business ownership helps significantly</li>
          <li>• <strong>Business plan quality:</strong> Professional assessment required</li>
          <li>• <strong>Dutch ties:</strong> Previous work/study in NL earns points</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Common Challenges</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• First-time entrepreneurs often struggle to reach 100 points</li>
          <li>• Business plan must be assessed by recognized advisor</li>
          <li>• "Added value" is subjectively evaluated</li>
          <li>• Process takes longer than DAFT</li>
          <li>• Higher refusal rate than DAFT applications</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>Points system reality check:</strong> The standard points system is designed for established entrepreneurs, not typical freelancers. If you're a web developer or consultant without prior business ownership, reaching 100 points is difficult. Consider whether Portugal, Germany, or Spain might offer easier paths.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Required Documents (Both Paths)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Valid passport:</strong> With at least 6 months validity</li>
      <li><strong>Business plan:</strong> Detailed for points system, simpler for DAFT</li>
      <li><strong>Proof of funds:</strong> €4,500 minimum for DAFT, more for points system</li>
      <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Proof of coverage or intent to obtain Dutch insurance</li>
      <li><strong>Antecedents certificate:</strong> Criminal background check from home country</li>
      <li><strong>Tuberculosis certificate:</strong> From designated clinic (some nationalities)</li>
      <li><strong>Application forms:</strong> Completed IND forms</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Insurance Requirements -->
  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">Dutch Health Insurance is Mandatory</h3>
      <p class="text-green-800">
        Unlike many countries where expat insurance satisfies visa requirements, the Netherlands requires all residents to have Dutch basic health insurance (basisverzekering). You must arrange this within 4 months of registering at your municipality. International insurance is only acceptable during your initial transition period.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Dutch healthcare system is based on mandatory private insurance with government regulation. Everyone pays for basic insurance (basisverzekering), which covers essential care. You can add optional supplementary insurance (aanvullende verzekering) for extras like dental care and physiotherapy.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Basic vs. Supplementary Insurance</h3>

    <ComparisonTable columns={insuranceColumns} rows={insuranceRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">How Dutch Insurance Works</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What You Must Know</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ <strong>Mandatory deductible:</strong> €385/year (2026) before insurance pays</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>GP visits:</strong> Free (no deductible applies)</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Referral system:</strong> Need GP referral for specialists</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Open enrollment:</strong> Switch insurers each January</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Zorgtoeslag:</strong> Low-income subsidy available</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Coverage Included in Basic</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>✓ GP consultations (huisarts)</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital care and surgery</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health care (limited sessions)</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care and midwife</li>
          <li>✓ Ambulance and emergency services</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>The deductible reality:</strong> The €385 mandatory deductible (eigen risico) means you pay the first €385 of most healthcare costs each year. This doesn't apply to GP visits, maternity care, or children under 18. Budget for this, especially in your first year when you may need healthcare more.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Insurance Timeline for New Arrivals</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Before Arrival</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Keep your international health insurance active. You may need to show proof of coverage for your visa application. Cigna Global or Allianz Care work well for this transition period.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">First 4 Months</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After registering at your municipality and receiving your BSN (citizen service number), you have 4 months to arrange Dutch basic insurance. Your international insurance can cover this gap, but don't delay—late registration may result in fines.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ongoing</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Once you have Dutch basic insurance, cancel your international policy. You can switch Dutch insurers every January during open enrollment. Consider supplementary insurance if you need dental or extensive physiotherapy coverage.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Freelancer tip:</strong> As a self-employed person (ZZP'er), you pay for your own health insurance—there's no employer contribution. Budget €1,500-2,000/year for basic insurance plus the €385 deductible. This is a significant fixed cost that affects your freelance rates.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA Box -->
  <CTABox
    variant="highlight"
    title="Need coverage during your transition to Dutch insurance?"
    description="International health insurance can bridge the gap before your Dutch basisverzekering is active."
    buttonText="Compare Transition Coverage"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <!-- Section: Recommended Providers -->
  <section id="recommended-providers" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      You'll need two types of insurance: international coverage for your visa application and transition period, then Dutch basic insurance once you're registered. Here are the top options for both phases.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Provider Recommendations by Situation</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Transition Period (First 4 Months)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Cigna Global or Allianz Care provide comprehensive coverage during your move. Both are widely recognized for visa applications and offer good coverage in the Netherlands. Cancel once Dutch insurance is active.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Long-term: Best Value Dutch Insurance</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">CZ offers competitive premiums with straightforward policies. Good for freelancers who want to minimize costs. Basic coverage is standardized by law, so choosing the cheapest insurer often makes sense.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Long-term: Best for Expats</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Zilveren Kruis and ONVZ offer excellent English-language support and are experienced with expat needs. Worth paying slightly more if you're uncomfortable navigating Dutch bureaucracy or prefer English-speaking customer service.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-amber-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">If You Need Dental Coverage</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dutch basic insurance doesn't cover adult dental care. Add a supplementary package (aanvullende verzekering) if you expect dental work. Most supplementary packages cost €10-40/month and cover 75-100% of dental costs up to a yearly maximum.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Choosing Your Dutch Insurer</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What to Compare</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Monthly premium:</strong> Varies by €10-30 between insurers</li>
          <li>• <strong>Customer service:</strong> English availability varies</li>
          <li>• <strong>Online tools:</strong> Apps, claim submission, doctor finder</li>
          <li>• <strong>Supplementary options:</strong> Dental, physio, alternative medicine</li>
          <li>• <strong>Collective discounts:</strong> Some employers/groups offer 5-10% off</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What Doesn't Matter</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Coverage quality:</strong> Basic coverage is identical by law</li>
          <li>• <strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> All must accept you for basic</li>
          <li>• <strong>Doctor access:</strong> Any GP accepts any basic insurance</li>
          <li>• <strong>Hospital coverage:</strong> All hospitals work with all insurers</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-green-800">
        <strong>Comparison sites:</strong> Use Independer.nl or Zorgwijzer.nl to compare Dutch health insurance. These sites show all insurers side-by-side with current premiums. You can filter by English support and see supplementary package options.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Costs Breakdown -->
