          <li>• Rules have been tightening—verify current requirements</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Dutch freelancer visa process involves applying for an MVV (entry visa) from your home country, then converting it to a residence permit after arrival. DAFT applicants have a more streamlined process, while points-system applicants need additional business plan assessments.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Prepare Your Business Plan</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">For DAFT, a simple business outline works—describe your services, target clients, and projected income. For the points system, you'll need a comprehensive plan assessed by a recognized advisor (RVO or designated organizations). Include market analysis, financial projections, and evidence of your expertise.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Open a Dutch Bank Account (DAFT)</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">DAFT applicants should open a Dutch bank account and deposit €4,500. Some banks allow account opening from abroad (bunq, for example). Alternatively, you can show funds in a US account with proof of transfer intent. Keep documentation of your capital.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submit MVV Application</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Apply at the Dutch embassy or consulate in your home country. Submit your passport, business plan, proof of funds, and application forms. Pay the visa fee (€207 for DAFT, €350+ for standard). Some countries allow online application through IND.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Wait for IND Decision</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">The IND (Immigration and Naturalisation Service) processes your application in the Netherlands. This takes 8-12 weeks, sometimes longer. You may be asked for additional documents. Track your application status online through the IND portal.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Collect MVV and Travel</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Once approved, collect your MVV sticker from the embassy. This entry visa is valid for 90 days—you must enter the Netherlands and register within this period. Book your flight and arrange initial accommodation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register at Municipality (Gemeente)</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Within 5 days of arrival, register at your local gemeente (city hall). You'll need your rental contract and passport. This registration gives you a BSN (citizen service number)—essential for banking, insurance, and everything else.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Collect Residence Permit</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Schedule an appointment at an IND desk to collect your residence permit card. Bring your passport and any requested documents. The card is your official proof of residence—valid for 2 years initially (DAFT) or as specified.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">8</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register at KvK (Chamber of Commerce)</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Visit the KvK to register your business. Bring your passport, residence permit, and business details. You'll receive a KvK number (like an EIN/company number) and be registered in the trade register. Cost is €75 one-time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">9</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Arrange Dutch Health Insurance</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Within 4 months of registration, sign up for Dutch basic health insurance. Compare providers online, choose your insurer, and submit your BSN. Coverage begins from your registration date (retroactively if needed). Cancel your international insurance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Housing first:</strong> Finding accommodation in the Netherlands (especially Amsterdam) is notoriously difficult. Start your search before arriving—you need an address to register at the gemeente. Consider short-term rentals initially, then search for permanent housing once you have your BSN.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Real-World Scenarios -->
  <section id="scenarios" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Here's how different situations typically play out for freelancers moving to the Netherlands:
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
