  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming International Insurance Will Work Long-term</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Netherlands requires Dutch basic insurance for all residents. International insurance works for your visa application and transition period, but you must switch to Dutch insurance within 4 months of registration. Failure to do so results in automatic enrollment and back-payment penalties.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the Points System Difficulty</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you're not eligible for DAFT, the points system is genuinely difficult for typical freelancers. It's designed for entrepreneurs creating jobs and bringing innovation—not solo consultants or developers. Research whether you can realistically score 100 points before investing time and money.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Securing Housing Before Arrival</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You need a Dutch address to register at the gemeente, which you need for your BSN, which you need for everything else. The Dutch housing market (especially Amsterdam) is extremely competitive. Start searching months in advance and consider short-term housing services for your first months.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting the Annual Insurance Deductible</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dutch insurance has a mandatory €385 annual deductible that catches many expats off guard. Unlike your premium, this is per-person and resets each January. Budget for it, especially in your first year when you might need more healthcare as you settle in.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming 30% Ruling Applies to All Freelancers</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The 30% ruling is a significant tax benefit, but it's not automatic for self-employed people. Many freelancers assume they'll qualify and are disappointed. Consult a Dutch tax advisor before factoring this benefit into your financial planning.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Netherlands -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in the Netherlands</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Dutch healthcare system consistently ranks among Europe's best, with universal coverage through mandatory private insurance. Care quality is high, wait times are generally reasonable, and English is widely spoken in medical settings—especially in major cities.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Dutch Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What's Covered (Basic Insurance)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP consultations (huisarts) - no deductible</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital care and surgeries</li>
          <li>✓ Specialist care (with GP referral)</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health care (some sessions)</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity and postnatal care</li>
          <li>✓ Ambulance services</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">What's Not Covered (Basic)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Adult dental care (covered for children)</li>
          <li>• Most physiotherapy (limited chronic care only)</li>
          <li>• Glasses and contact lenses</li>
          <li>• Cosmetic procedures</li>
          <li>• Alternative medicine (acupuncture, etc.)</li>
          <li>• Most vaccinations (travel vaccines)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The GP Gatekeeper System</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      In the Netherlands, your huisarts (GP/family doctor) is your first point of contact for almost all healthcare. You must register with a GP near your home, and you'll need a referral from them to see specialists. This is different from the US system where you can often see specialists directly.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Finding a GP (Huisarts)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Register with a GP practice near your home as soon as you have your BSN. Many practices have waiting lists in popular areas. Use Zorgkaart Nederland to find practices accepting new patients and read reviews. Most GPs in cities speak English.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Getting Referrals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dutch GPs often take a "wait and see" approach that can frustrate expats used to more interventionist medicine. Be direct about your concerns if you feel you need a specialist. GPs can refer you to any specialist; you don't need to stay within your insurance network.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Urgent Care</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">For urgent but non-emergency issues outside GP hours, call your GP's practice—they'll connect you to the huisartsenpost (after-hours GP service). For true emergencies, call 112 or go directly to the hospital's spoedeisende hulp (emergency room).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Quality</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>High quality:</strong> Netherlands consistently ranks in top 5 European healthcare systems</li>
      <li><strong>English widely spoken:</strong> Medical professionals in cities typically speak good English</li>
      <li><strong>Short wait times:</strong> Generally quick access to GPs; specialists may have 2-6 week waits</li>
      <li><strong>Modern facilities:</strong> Well-equipped hospitals and clinics throughout the country</li>
      <li><strong>Pharmacy access:</strong> Prescriptions filled at apotheek (pharmacy), often same-day</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Cultural note:</strong> Dutch healthcare culture emphasizes not over-treating. If you come from a country with more interventionist medicine (like the US), you may find Dutch doctors less likely to prescribe antibiotics, order tests, or refer to specialists for minor issues. This is intentional, not negligence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the DAFT treaty and who qualifies?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Dutch-American Friendship Treaty (DAFT) is a 1956 agreement that allows US citizens to become self-employed in the Netherlands with minimal requirements—just €4,500 in business capital and a viable business plan. Japanese citizens have similar access under a parallel treaty. No points system, no proof of "added value."
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I really need Dutch health insurance, or can I use international insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, Dutch basic health insurance (basisverzekering) is mandatory for all residents. International insurance can cover your visa application and first 4 months, but you must switch to Dutch insurance after registering. Failure to do so results in automatic enrollment and fines. This is non-negotiable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How hard is the points system for non-DAFT applicants?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Genuinely difficult for typical freelancers. You need 100 points across experience, business plan quality, and "added value to the Netherlands." Solo consultants and developers often struggle because they don't create jobs or bring obvious innovation. Many non-DAFT freelancers consider Portugal or Germany as alternatives.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Dutch to freelance in the Netherlands?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not for business or daily life—over 90% of Dutch people speak English, and business is commonly conducted in English. However, official documents are in Dutch, and speaking some Dutch helps with integration and certain administrative tasks. For permanent residence or citizenship, Dutch language requirements apply.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the 30% ruling and do freelancers qualify?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The 30% ruling allows qualifying expats to receive 30% of their salary tax-free for up to 5 years. However, self-employed people don't automatically qualify—it's designed for employees. Some freelancers set up a BV (Dutch private company) and pay themselves as employees to qualify. Consult a tax advisor for your specific situation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence or citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Permanent residence is possible after 5 years of legal residence. Citizenship requires 5 years plus passing a civic integration exam (inburgeringsexamen) in Dutch. The Netherlands generally doesn't allow dual citizenship—you may need to renounce your current citizenship, though exceptions exist for some countries.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands offers an excellent base for freelancers who value a central European location, English-speaking environment, and strong business infrastructure. For US and Japanese citizens, the DAFT treaty makes it one of the easiest European countries to access—far simpler than Germany's complex requirements or Portugal's income thresholds.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      However, the mandatory Dutch health insurance system means higher fixed costs than countries accepting international insurance. Budget €1,800-2,200 annually for insurance and deductible, on top of some of Europe's highest living costs (especially housing in Amsterdam). This works for higher-earning freelancers but can squeeze those with modest incomes.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For non-DAFT applicants, think carefully before committing. The points system is genuinely difficult for typical freelancers without established businesses or innovative offerings. Portugal's D7 visa, Spain's digital nomad visa, or Germany's freelancer visa may offer easier paths with lower costs.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        The Netherlands is ideal for US/Japanese freelancers seeking a European base with excellent infrastructure and English-speaking culture. DAFT makes it accessible; just be prepared for mandatory Dutch insurance and high living costs. Non-DAFT applicants should carefully evaluate whether they can score 100 points before investing in the process.
      </p>
